The git fetch command is used to download branches, commits, files, and references from a remote repository into your local repository without automatically applying or merging them into your current working files.
This process updates your local copy of the remote repository (known as "remote-tracking branches," e.g., origin/main), allowing you to view and review changes before deciding how to integrate them into your local workspace. 
Key Characteristics
Safe and Non-Disruptive: git fetch does not modify your current working directory or local branches, which prevents merge conflicts from occurring immediately.
Provides Overview: It allows you to see what changes others on the team have committed and how far your local branch is ahead or behind the remote branch using commands like git log or git diff.
Prerequisite for Merging: After fetching, you must manually use a separate command, such as git merge or git rebase, to integrate the downloaded changes into your local branch. 
